name: 1,3-diethyl-5-methylbenzene
Reason: 1,3-diethyl-5-methylbenzene has a melting point that can be predicted by analyzing its structural components. The basic unit for comparison is ethylbenzene, which has a melting point of -114.1 °C. The introduction of two methyl groups and one ethyl group increases the molecular weight and size, which raises the melting point. The methyl groups also contribute to hydrogen bonding, which can lower the melting point. The ethyl group, on the other hand, reduces the melting point due to its smaller size and lower molecular weight. The net effect is a complex interplay between these structural components, but the methyl groups are expected to dominate due to their higher molecular weight and hydrogen bonding potential.
